problems in applied market design siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project problems in applied market design title problems in applied market design principal investigator jonathan levin dates september 1 2009 august 31 2012 sponsor national science foundation economic analysis has played an increasing role in shaping the design of market rules and institutions the proposed research will use economic theory and empirical methods to study a series of applied market design problems the first project relates to the design of radio spectrum auctions with the goal of documenting some surprising empirical regularities and explaining the role of strategic bidding behavior a second project studies the college admissions market again documenting a set of empirical facts and providing a model of market equilibrium that matches the empirical patterns a third project studies the problem of selling dated goods with an empirical application to the market for graphical internet advertising finally a fourth project analyzes a class of advanced market commitment mechanisms that have been proposed as a way to promote the development of vaccines for developing countries here the empirical application is to the design of a market based program for pneumococcal vaccine the proposal also highlights some additional theoretical and empirical problems likely to arise in the course of the research stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
